Grenada has put measures in place to limit the spread of coronavirus (COVID-19).
For information on how to return to the UK from Grenada, see Return to the UK
Local measures
Government announced a limited State of Emergency from 25 March with a 24 hour curfew and restriction on activities to limit the spread of the virus. You should keep up to date with the Emergency Powers Regulations on the Government Information Service Facebook page.
The Ministry of Health Grenada is asking the public to call the COVID-19 enquiries information line on 538 4787 or 458 4787 or the police on 440 3999 if they have any symptoms such as cough fever or difficulty breathing.
Travel restrictions
With the announcement of the airport closure from 23 March, incoming passengers are no longer allowed to enter Grenada. From 16 March, disembarkation from cruise vessels will also not be permitted in Grenada. Effective 22 March, non-Grenadian passengers and crew on yachts will not be permitted to disembark in Grenada, Carriacou, and Petite Martinique. Any failure to comply will result in a fine or detention.
Visas
The Government of Grenada has granted permission for the immigration status of British national visitors to be automatically extended to cover their stay during the period of coronavirus pandemic and/or the period of the current state of emergency without incurring any penalty.
If you wish to stay beyond the period mentioned, you are advised to visit the immigration office to secure the necessary adjustment as soon as Grenada returns to period of normality.
Further information
See the TravelHealthPro website for further advice on travel abroad and reducing spread of respiratory viruses during the COVID-19 pandemic.
